answer_to_ill_with_hint:
The question's premises are based on a misunderstanding of the nature of the function. The function in question is the Dirichlet function, which is defined as follows:

\[
f(x) = 
\begin{cases} 
1 & \text{if } x \text{ is rational} \\
0 & \text{if } x \text{ is irrational}
\end{cases}
\]

This function is discontinuous everywhere because, in any interval, no matter how small, there are both rational and irrational numbers. Therefore, the function does not have a limit at any point, and it cannot be continuous at any point.

Thus, the function is not continuous.
